Here’s a structured **summary of core topics, concepts, and principles** essential for the exam, followed by **Mermaid knowledge graphs** to visualize relationships. --- ## **Core Topics & Concepts Summary** ### **1. JavaScript & DOM Events** - **Event Propagation**: Bubbling (child → parent) vs. Capturing (parent → child). - Default: Bubbling (e.g., clicking a `` triggers `table` event *after* the `` event). - **Key Example**: ```javascript document.getElementById("table_id").addEventListener("click", () => console.log("Table")); document.getElementById("cell_id_1").addEventListener("click", () => console.log("Cell")); ``` - Clicking `"Abhishek"` logs: `"Cell"` → `"Table"` (bubbling). - If `stopPropagation()` is called in the cell handler, only `"Cell"` logs. - **Event Listeners**: Order matters. Later listeners execute *after* earlier ones. - **`this` Binding**: - In methods, `this` refers to the object calling it. - **`call(obj)`** binds `this` to `obj`: ```javascript obj2.second.call(obj1); // `this` inside `second` refers to `obj1`. ``` --- ### **2. Vue.js** #### **Directives** | Directive | Purpose | Example | |------------|------------------------------------------|----------------------------------| | `v-bind` | Bind HTML attributes to data. | `:href="url"` | | `v-model` | Two-way data binding (form inputs). | `v-model="name"` | | `v-cloak` | Hide uncompiled mustache tags (`{{ }}`). | `
{{ message }}
` | | `v-on` | Bind event listeners. | `@click="handler"` | #### **Lifecycle Hooks** - **`created`**: Called after instance creation (data/reactivity set up). - **`mounted`**: Called after DOM insertion (use for DOM manipulations). - **Example**: ```javascript mounted() { this.message = "Hello from mounted"; // Overrides `created`. } ``` #### **Vue Router** - **Dynamic Routes**: Use `:id` in paths (e.g., `/student/:id`). - **Nested Routes**: Children routes render inside `` of the parent. - **Example**: ```javascript routes: [ { path: '/', component: Home, children: [ { path: 'student/:id', component: Student, props: true } ] } ] ``` - **Navigation**: Use `` or `this.$router.push()`. - **404 Handling**: Use `path: '*'` to catch all unmatched routes. #### **Vuex (State Management)** - **Mutations**: Synchronous state updates. - **Commit Mutations**: ```javascript this.$store.commit("update_total_cost", payload); ``` - **Define Mutations**: ```javascript mutations: { update_total_cost(state, payload) { state.total_cost = payload.count * payload.price; } } ``` --- ### **3. Asynchronous JavaScript** #### **Promises** - **States**: Pending → Fulfilled (`resolve`) or Rejected (`reject`). - **Chaining**: - `.then()`: Handles fulfillment. - `.catch()`: Handles rejection. - `.finally()`: Executes regardless of outcome. - **Example**: ```javascript new Promise((resolve, reject) => { if (condition) resolve("Success"); else reject("Error"); }) .then(data => console.log(data)) .catch(err => console.error(err)) .finally(() => console.log("Done")); ``` #### **Async/Await** - **`await`**: Pauses execution until the promise settles. - **Error Handling**: Use `try/catch`. ```javascript async function fetchData() { try { const data = await fetch(url); console.log(data); } catch (err) { console.error(err); } } ``` #### **Event Loop & Concurrency** - **Microtasks (Promises)** > **Macrotasks (setTimeout, I/O)**. - **Celery (Python)**: - Asynchronous task queue for background jobs. - **Workers**: Parallel task execution (more workers → faster completion). - **Example**: ```python @celery.task def generate_report(user): # Long-running task pass ``` --- ### **4. Flask & Caching** #### **Flask-Caching** - **Decorators**: - `@cache.cached(timeout=100)`: Caches responses (key includes route + args). - **Redis**: Used as a backend for distributed caching. - **Latency**: - **First Request**: Executes function (e.g., `time.sleep(30)`). - **Subsequent Requests**: Returns cached response (near-instant). #### **CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)** - **Headers**: - `Access-Control-Allow-Origin`: Specifies allowed origins. - `Accept`: Client tells server preferred response type (e.g., `application/json`). - **Same-Origin Policy**: `http://example.com` ≠ `http://sub.example.com` (unless CORS allows). --- ### **5. Web Performance & Optimization** #### **Caching Strategies** | Type | Description | Example | |--------------------|----------------------------------------------|----------------------------------| | **Browser Cache** | Stores static assets (HTML, CSS, JS). | `Cache-Control: max-age=3600` | | **Backend Cache** | Stores dynamic data (e.g., API responses). | Redis, Memcached | | **Database** | Indexes, materialized views, partitioning. | `CREATE INDEX idx_column ON table(column)` | #### **Polling Techniques** | Technique | Description | Pros/Cons | |-----------------|----------------------------------------------|------------------------------------| | **Short Polling** | Client polls server at fixed intervals. | Simple; inefficient for frequent updates. | | **Long Polling** | Server holds request until data is available. | Reduces latency; complex. | | **WebSockets** | Full-duplex communication. | Real-time; persistent connection. | #### **Lighthouse Metrics** - **First Contentful Paint (FCP)**: Time to render first DOM content. - **Largest Contentful Paint (LCP)**: Time to render largest element (e.g., hero image). --- ### **6. Security** | Concept | Description | |-----------------------|----------------------------------------------| | **Denial of Service (DoS)** | Overwhelms server with requests. **Not** code injection. | | **CORS** | Controls cross-origin requests via headers. | | **Privacy vs. Security** | Privacy = data protection; Security = system protection. | --- ### **7. Database Optimization** | Strategy | Description | Example | |-------------------|----------------------------------------------|----------------------------------| | **Indexing** | Speeds up queries on indexed columns. | `CREATE INDEX idx_column ON table(column)` | | **Partitioning** | Splits table into smaller chunks. | `PARTITION BY LIST(column)` | | **Materialized Views** | Precomputes aggregations. | `CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW ...` | | **Caching** | Stores query results (e.g., total scores). | Redis, backend cache. | --- ### **8. State Management** | State Type | Description | Example | |------------------|----------------------------------------------|----------------------------------| | **Ephemeral** | Temporary UI state (lost on refresh). | Loading spinners, active tab. | | **Persistent** | Saved across sessions (e.g., localStorage). | User preferences, shopping cart. | --- ## **Mermaid Knowledge Graphs** ### **1. JavaScript Event Propagation** ```mermaid graph TD A[Click Event on TD] --> B[TD Event Listener] B --> C[Table Event Listener (Bubbling)] A --> D[stopPropagation] D --> E[Only TD Listener Fires] ``` ### **2. Vue.js Core Concepts** ```mermaid graph TD A[Vue Instance] --> B[Lifecycle Hooks] B --> B1[created] B --> B2[mounted] A --> C[Directives] C --> C1[v-bind] C --> C2[v-model] C --> C3[v-on] A --> D[Vue Router] D --> D1[Nested Routes] D --> D2[Dynamic Segments] A --> E[Vuex] E --> E1[State] E --> E2[Mutations] ``` ### **3. Asynchronous JavaScript** ```mermaid graph TD A[Promise] --> B[Pending] B --> C1[Fulfilled] B --> C2[Rejected] C1 --> D[.then()] C2 --> E[.catch()] D --> F[.finally()] E --> F A --> G[Async/Await] G --> H[try/catch] ``` ### **4. Flask & Caching** ```mermaid graph TD A[Flask App] --> B[Route /name/] B --> C[Cache Check] C -->|Miss| D[Execute Function] D --> E[Sleep 30s] E --> F[Cache Response] C -->|Hit| G[Return Cached] ``` ### **5. Web Performance** ```mermaid graph TD A[Performance Optimization] --> B[Caching] B --> B1[Browser Cache] B --> B2[Backend Cache] A --> C[Database] C --> C1[Indexing] C --> C2[Partitioning] A --> D[Polling] D --> D1[Short Polling] D --> D2[WebSockets] ``` ### **6. Security Concepts** ```mermaid graph TD A[Web Security] --> B[CORS] B --> B1[Access-Control-Allow-Origin] A --> C[DoS] C --> C1[Not Code Injection] A --> D[Privacy vs. Security] D --> D1[Privacy: Data Protection] D --> D2[Security: System Protection] ``` ### **7. State Management** ```mermaid graph TD A[State] --> B[Ephemeral] B --> B1[Loading Spinners] B --> B2[Active Tab] A --> C[Persistent] C --> C1[localStorage] C --> C2[Shopping Cart] ```
